Category:2010s ballads]]\n[[Category:Eurovision Song Contest winning songs]]\n[[Category:Eurovision songs of 2017]]\n[[Category:Eurovision songs of Portugal]]\n[[Category:Portuguese songs]]\n[[Category:Portuguese-language songs]]\n[[Category:Songs about heartache]]\n[[Category:Vocal jazz songs]]\n[[Category:Number-one singles in Iceland]]\n[[Category:Number-one singles in Portugal]]\n[[Category:Golden Globes (Portugal) winners]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2017 song by Salvador Sobral}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name          = Amar pelos dois\n| cover         = Salvador Sobral - Amar pelos dois.jpg\n| alt           =\n| type          = single\n| artist        = [[Salvador Sobral]]\n| album         =\n| language      = Portuguese\n| English_title = \"To Love for the Both of Us\"\n| released      = 10 March 2017\n| format        = {{hlist|[[CD single]]|[[Music download|digital download]]|[[Streaming media|streaming]]}}\n| recorded      =\n| studio        =\n| venue         =\n| genre         = {{hlist|[[Waltz_(music)#Jazz_waltzes|Jazz waltz]]|[[baroque pop]]|[[bossa nova]]}}\n| length        = 3:05\n| label         = Sons em Tr\u00e2nsito\n| writer        = {{Hlist|[[Lu\u00edsa Sobral]]}}\n| producer      = Lu\u00edsa Sobral\n| prev_title    = [[Nem Eu]]\n| prev_year     = 2016\n| next_title    = [[Mano a Mano (song)|Mano a Mano]]\n| next_year     = 2018\n| misc          = {{Infobox song contest entry\n| embed        = yes\n| song         = {{flagicon|Portugal}} \"Amar pelos dois\"\n| year         = 2017\n| country      = Portugal\n| artist       = [[Salvador Sobral]]\n| language     = Portuguese\n| composer     = [[Lu\u00edsa Sobral]]\n| lyricist     = Lu\u00edsa Sobral\n| place        = 1st\n| points       = 758\n| place_semi   = 1st\n| points_semi  = 370\n| prev         = H\u00e1 um mar que nos separa\n| prev_year    = 2015\n| prev_link    = H\u00e1 um mar que nos separa\n| next         = O jardim\n| next_year    = 2018\n| next_link    = O jardim\n}}\n}}\n\n\"'''Amar pelos dois'''\" ({{IPA-pt|\u0250\u02c8ma\u027e \u02c8p(\u0268)lu\u0283 \u02c8doj\u0283}}; English: To Love for the Both of Us) is a song performed by Portuguese singer [[Salvador Sobral]]. The track was written and produced by [[Lu\u00edsa Sobral]]. It premiered on 19 February 2017, when it was performed during the first semi-final of [[Festival da Can\u00e7\u00e3o|Festival da Can\u00e7\u00e3o 2017]], Portugal's national selection for the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2017]], and was released as a [[Music download|digital download]] on 10 March 2017 by Sons em Tr\u00e2nsito. \n\n\"Amar pelos dois\" is a [[Waltz_(music)#Jazz_waltzes|jazz waltz]] with a lyrical theme of [[broken heart|heartbreak]] after a [[breakup]]. The track received praise from [[Music journalism|music critics]] \u2013 some reviewers considered it Portugal's all-time best Eurovision entry. The song earned the Sobral siblings various awards, including two [[Marcel Bezen\u00e7on Awards]]. It was included in the [[European Union]] Songbook as the all-time top Portuguese [[love song]], and was covered by several artists. The song achieved [[Record chart|commercial success]], particularly in [[Europe]].\n\n\"Amar pelos dois\" represented {{Esccnty|Portugal}} in the Eurovision Song Contest 2017 in [[Kiev]], Ukraine. The song gave Portugal its first ever win since their debut in {{Escyr|1964}}. It amassed 758 points, setting the record for the highest number of points in the history of the [[Eurovision Song Contest|competition]], and is the only entry to top both the televoting and jury voting in the second half of the [[2010s]]. Salvador Sobral performed alone on stage B, close to the audience, while the background [[LED display|LED screens]] displayed an [[enchanted forest]].\n\n== Background and release==\n{{Quote box|width=25%|align=left|bgcolor=#c6dbf7|quote=\"I wanted to write a song that represents me, that could be on a record of mine, a song that I could be proud of and that's what I did.\"<ref name=\"eurovision.tv\">{{cite web|url=https://eurovision.tv/story/salvador-sobral-has-love-enough-for-portugal-and-europe|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20171126203452/https://eurovision.tv/story/salvador-sobral-has-love-enough-for-portugal-and-europe|website=eurovision.tv|title=Salvador Sobral has love enough for Portugal and Europe|publisher=[[European Broadcasting Union]]|last=M. Escudero|first=Victor|date=March 6, 2017|archivedate=November 26, 2017}}</ref>|source=\u2014Lu\u00edsa Sobral, composer of \"Amar pelos dois\"}}\n\"Amar pelos dois\" was one of sixteen songs commissioned by [[R\u00e1dio e Televis\u00e3o de Portugal|RTP]] for [[Festival da Can\u00e7\u00e3o|Festival da Can\u00e7\u00e3o 2017]], Portugal's national selection for the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2017]]. The composers both created the song and selected the performer for their entry. Lu\u00edsa Sobral composed \"Amar pelos dois\" specifically for her brother, Salvador Sobral: \"I never thought about singing this song myself because when I wrote it I already had my brother's voice in mind. I was very fond of seeing him playing my song, because I think he is an extraordinary singer and because it gives me great joy to see him at the song contest and also that it turned out to be a family thing\".<ref name=\"eurovision.tv\"/> Salvador Sobral stated that even though \"Amar pelos dois\" was created by his sister Lu\u00edsa, she gave him freedom to perform the song according to his artistic personality.<ref name=\"eurovision.tv\"/>\n\n\"Amar pelos dois\" premiered on 19 February 2017, when it was performed in [[Festival da Can\u00e7\u00e3o|Festival da Can\u00e7\u00e3o 2017]], Portugal's national selection for the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2017]]. The song became available through [[Music download|digital]] retailers and [[Streaming media|streaming]] services on 10 March 2017 via Sons em Tr\u00e2nsito.<ref name=\"iTunes\">{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/pt/album/amar-pelos-dois-single/id1213997535|title=Amar pelos dois - Single|website=[[iTunes Store]]|accessdate=10 March 2017}}</ref> On 16 June 2017, it was released on [[CD single|physical format]] via [[Sony Music]].<ref name=\"CD single\">{{cite web|url=http://media.rtp.pt/festivaldacancao/artigos/cd-single-amar-pelos-dois-lancado-16-junho/|title=CD Single \u201cAmar Pelos Dois\u201d \u00e9 lan\u00e7ado a 16 de junho|website=[[R\u00e1dio e Televis\u00e3o de Portugal|RTP]]|language=pt|accessdate=December 12, 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Composition ==\n\"Amar pelos dois\" was written and produced by Lu\u00edsa Sobral, Salvador Sobral's sister. \"Amar pelos dois\" is a [[Waltz_(music)#Jazz_waltzes|jazz waltz]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.vaterland.li/kultur/news/Aus-fuer-die-Schweiz-am-Song-Contest;art106,268718|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170706234812/http://www.vaterland.li/kultur/news/Aus-fuer-die-Schweiz-am-Song-Contest;art106,268718|title=Aus f\u00fcr die Schweiz am Song Contest|work=[[Liechtensteiner Vaterland]]|publisher=Vaduzer Medienhaus AG|date=May 11, 2017|archivedate=July 6, 2017|language=de}}</ref> with a length of three minutes and five seconds (3:05)<ref name=\"iTunes\"/> that moves at a [[tempo]] of 92 beats per minute.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://escnation.com/news/?id=1240|title=Ballad or up-tempo? Let's take a look at the actual tempo of this year's entries|publisher=ESC Nation|author=Jonas|date=March 21, 2017}}</ref> The song is composed in the [[Key (music)|key]] of [[F major]] and is written in [[triple metre]], with Sobral's vocals spanning from D<sub>4</sub> to G<sub>5</sub>.<ref>{{cite web|last=Sobral|first=Salvador|title=Amar Pelos Dois By Salvador Sobral - Digital Sheet Music|url=http://www.musicnotes.com/sheetmusic/mtd.asp?ppn=MN0174501|website=Musicnotes.com|publisher=[[Sony/ATV Music Publishing]]|accessdate=June 16, 2017}}</ref> Without [[Backing vocalist|background vocals]], it has an [[Instrumentation (music)|instrumentation]] consisting of [[Violin family|strings]] and [[piano]]. Salvador Sobral stated that \"Amar pelos dois\" is \"influenced by those old songs from the [[Great American Songbook]], and it also has a touch of the beautiful [[bossa nova]] melodies\".<ref name=\"ESC Bubble\">{{cite web|url=http://escbubble.com/2017/02/salvador-sobral-amar-pelos-dois-love-song-sad-one/ |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170403215105/http://escbubble.com/2017/02/salvador-sobral-amar-pelos-dois-love-song-sad-one/ |title=Salvador Sobral: \"Amar pelos dois\" is a love song. A sad one. |publisher=ESC Bubble |author=Juh\u00e1sz, Ervin |date=February 16, 2017 |archivedate=April 3, 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The song's lyrical theme is [[broken heart|heartbreak]] after a [[breakup]]:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wiwibloggs.com/2017/03/18/amar-pelos-dois-lyrics-salvador-sobral-portugal-eurovision-2017/181079/ |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170323164438/http://wiwibloggs.com/2017/03/18/amar-pelos-dois-lyrics-salvador-sobral-portugal-eurovision-2017/181079/ |title=\u201cAmar pelos dois\u201d lyrics \u2014 Salvador Sobral (Portugal, Eurovision 2017) |website=[[Wiwibloggs]] |date=March 18, 2017 |archivedate=March 23, 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref> \"Meu bem / Ouve as minhas preces / Pe\u00e7o que regresses / Que me voltes a querer\".{{refn|group=nb|In English translation: \"My love / Listen to my pleas / I beg you to come back / To want me again\".}} Sobral described it as \"a [[love song]]. A sad one\".<ref name=\"ESC Bubble\"/>\n\n== At Eurovision ==\n{{Main article|Portugal in the Eurovision Song Contest 2017}}\n=== National selection ===\nLu\u00edsa Sobral was announced as a participating songwriter in [[Festival da Can\u00e7\u00e3o|Festival da Can\u00e7\u00e3o 2017]], Portugal's national selection for the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2017]], on 5 December 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://esctoday.com/138971/portugal-three-shows-festival-da-cancao-2017-final-5-march|title=Portugal: Three shows for Festival da Can\u00e7\u00e3o 2017; final on 5 March|publisher=ESCToday|last=Jiandani|first=Sanjay|date=5 December 2016|accessdate=6 December 2016}}</ref> On 18 January 2017, her brother, Salvador Sobral, was announced to be performing her song, titled \"Amar pelos dois\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://media.rtp.pt/festivaldacancao/artigos/conheca-os-interpretes-da-1-semifinal-do-festival-da-cancao-2017/|title=Conhe\u00e7a os int\u00e9rpretes da 1.\u00aa Semifinal do Festival da Can\u00e7\u00e3o 2017|work=RTP.pt|accessdate=18 January 2017|language=pt|date=18 January 2017}}</ref> After being sent two songs by Lu\u00edsa Sobral, written for the competition, Salvador Sobral selected \"Amar pelos dois\" as the song he would like to perform. Lu\u00eds Figueiredo, who did the string arrangement, also chose \"Amar pelos dois\" as the song to go through the competition's various phases. Sobral competed in the first semi-final on February 19, placing second with 20 points after winning the jury vote and coming third in the televote.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wiwibloggs.com/2017/02/19/portugal-festival-da-cancao-semi-final-qualifiers/175666/|title=PORTUGAL: VIVA LA DIVA AND FERNANDO DANIEL AMONG QUALIFIERS IN FIRST SEMI-FINAL OF FESTIVAL DA CAN\u00c7\u00c3O 2017|date=19 February 2017|publisher=Wiwibloggs|website=wiwibloggs.com|last=Fuster|first=Luis}}</ref> In the final, held on 5 March, he won the jury vote and came second in the televote, placing first with 22 points and thus representing Portugal at the Eurovision Song Contest 2017.<ref name=\"win\">{{cite web|url=http://wiwibloggs.com/2017/03/06/portugal-salvador-sobral-wins-festival-da-cancao-2017/179145/|title=Portugal: Salvador Sobral wins Festival da Can\u00e7\u00e3o 2017 with \"Amar pelos dois\"|last=Foster|first=Luis|date=6 March 2017|publisher=Wiwibloggs|website=wiwibloggs.com}}</ref><ref name=\"Mercereau\">{{cite news|last1=Mercereau|first1=Damien|title=Eurovision 2017 : le Portugal de retour avec Salvador Sobral|url=http://tvmag.lefigaro.fr/programme-tv/eurovision-2017-le-portugal-de-retour-avec-salvador-sobral_1cb2ee44-0259-11e7-aad0-d9371b2c396c/|accessdate=16 March 2017|newspaper=Le Figaro|date=6 March 2017|language=fr}}</ref>\n\n=== In Kiev ===\n{{multiple image\n<!--image 1-->\n | image1            = ESC2017 Televote Portugal.svg\n | caption1          = Points awarded to Portugal by each national televote\n<!--image 2-->\n | image2            = ESC2017 Jury Portugal.svg\n | caption2          = Points awarded to Portugal by each national jury\n}}\nThe [[Eurovision Song Contest 2017]] took place at the [[International Exhibition Centre]] in [[Kiev]], Ukraine and consisted of two semi-finals on 9 and 11 May, and the final on 13 May 2017. Portugal was drawn to compete in the first half of the first semi-final.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://eurovision.tv/story/results-of-the-semi-final-allocation-draw |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170515142127/https://eurovision.tv/story/results-of-the-semi-final-allocation-draw |website=eurovision.tv |title=Results of the Semi-Final Allocation Draw |publisher=[[European Broadcasting Union]] |last1=Jordan |first1=Paul |last2=Nilsson |first2=Helena |date=January 31, 2017 |archivedate=May 15, 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The running order for the semi-finals was decided by the producers, in order to avoid similar songs being placed next to each other. Portugal was set to perform in position 9, following the entry from {{Esccnty|Azerbaijan|y=2017}} and before the entry from {{Esccnty|Greece|y=2017}}.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://eurovision.tv/story/running-order-eurovision-2017-revealed |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170612000755/https://eurovision.tv/story/running-order-eurovision-2017-revealed |title=Semi-Final running order for Eurovision 2017 revealed |website=eurovision.tv |publisher=[[European Broadcasting Union]] |last=Jordan |first=Paul |date=March 31, 2017 |archivedate=June 12, 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref> For the grand final, Portugal was drawn to compete in the first half. Portugal was subsequently placed to perform in position 11 by the producers, following the entry from {{Esccnty|Denmark|y=2017}} and before the entry from Azerbaijan.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://eurovision.tv/story/running-order-grand-final-2017 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170512103306/https://eurovision.tv/story/running-order-grand-final-2017 |title=EXCLUSIVE: Running order for the 2017 Grand Final released! |website=eurovision.tv |publisher=[[European Broadcasting Union]] |last1=Jordan |first1=Paul |last2=Nilsson |first2=Helena |date=May 11, 2017 |archivedate=May 12, 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Salvador Sobral was one of the favorites to win the contest according to [[Bookmaker|bookmakers]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tvi24.iol.pt/musica/festival-da-cancao/salvador-sobral-ja-e-primeiro-nas-apostas-para-ganhar-eurovisao|title=Salvador Sobral j\u00e1 \u00e9 primeiro nas apostas para ganhar Eurovis\u00e3o|website=[[TVI 24]]|date=May 12, 2017|language=pt}}</ref> With its tool The Eurosearch Song Contest, [[Google]] correctly predicted Sobral's victory.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://googletrends.github.io/eurosearch-song-contest/|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180511013245/https://googletrends.github.io/eurosearch-song-contest/|title=The Eurosearch Song Contest|website=[[Google]]|archivedate=May 11, 2018}}</ref> For the winner's encore, siblings Salvador and Lu\u00edsa sang the song as a duet, just like they did in the national final.\n\nFor his performance, Salvador Sobral wore a black suit and performed alone on stage B, close to the audience. During the performance, the background [[LED display|LED screens]] displays an [[enchanted forest]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.escportugal.pt/2017/05/esc2017-as-reacoes-ao-segundo-ensaio-de.html|title=ESC2017: As rea\u00e7\u00f5es ao segundo ensaio de Portugal|website=ESC Portugal|date=May 4, 2017|language=pt}}</ref> \n\nSalvador Sobral's victory was hailed in Portugal by the [[Assembly of the Republic (Portugal)|Assembly of the Republic]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.escportugal.pt/2017/05/parlamento-de-pe-para-aplaudir-salvador.html|title=[V\u00cdDEO] Parlamento de p\u00e9 para aplaudir Salvador e Lu\u00edsa Sobral|website=ESC Portugal|date=May 19, 2017|language=pt}}</ref> [[Prime Minister of Portugal|Prime Minister]] [[Ant\u00f3nio Costa]],<ref>{{cite tweet|user=antoniocostapm|number=863525180861231104|date=May 13, 2017|title=Fez-se hist\u00f3ria em portugu\u00eas hoje na #Eurovis\u00e3o! Parab\u00e9ns Salvador! Parab\u00e9ns Portugal! #Eurovision}}</ref> [[Ministry of Culture (Portugal)|Minister of Culture]] [[Lu\u00eds Filipe Castro Mendes]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.escportugal.pt/2017/05/portugal-ministro-da-cultura-diz-que.html|title=Portugal: Ministro da Cultura diz que vit\u00f3ria na Eurovis\u00e3o \u00e9 prova da criatividade lusa |website=ESC Portugal|date=May 15, 2017|language=pt}}</ref> and [[President of Portugal|President]] [[Marcelo Rebelo de Sousa]] who distinguished the Sobral siblings with the [[Order of Merit (Portugal)|Order of Merit]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.publico.pt/2018/04/23/culturaipsilon/noticia/luisa-e-salvador-sobral-nomeados-comendadores-pelo-exito-singular-1811456|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180818140027/https://www.publico.pt/2018/04/23/culturaipsilon/noticia/luisa-e-salvador-sobral-nomeados-comendadores-pelo-exito-singular-1811456|title=Irm\u00e3os Sobral nomeados comendadores por \"\u00eaxito singular\"|work=[[P\u00fablico (Portugal)|P\u00fablico]]|date=April 23, 2018|archivedate=August 18, 2018|language=pt}}</ref>\n\n==== Record-breaking victory ====\nBy earning 758 points overall in the grand final, \"Amar pelos dois\" became the highest-scoring entry in the history of the [[Eurovision Song Contest]], overtaking {{Esccnty|Ukraine|y=2016}}'s \"[[1944 (song)|1944]]\" which had scored 534 points the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2016|year before]]. \"Amar pelos dois\" is the only entry to top both the televoting and jury voting in the second half of the [[2010s]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Eurovision 2017 Results: Voting & Points |url=http://eurovisionworld.com/?eurovision=2017 |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20170616021651/http://eurovisionworld.com/?eurovision=2017 |website=Eurovision World |accessdate=June 16, 2017 |archivedate=June 16, 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In the grand final, \"Amar pelos dois\" received at least five televote points from every participating country.<ref name=Scoreboard/> It is the first winning song entirely performed in a country's native language since {{Esccnty|Serbia|y=2007}}'s \"[[Molitva]]\" ({{Escyr|2007}}) and the first winning song written in [[triple metre]] since {{Esccnty|Ireland|y=1996}}'s \"[[The Voice (Eimear Quinn song)|The Voice]]\" ({{Escyr|1996}}). With 382 points awarded by the national juries, \"Amar pelos dois\" broke the record of most jury points ever, beating {{Esccnty|Sweden|y=2015}}'s \"[[Heroes (M\u00e5ns Zelmerl\u00f6w song)|Heroes]]\" which received 353 points from the juries in {{Escyr|2015}}.<ref name=\"Scoreboard\"/> Additionally, Portugal achieved the biggest winning margin of the decade and the second biggest of all time, scoring 143 more points than the [[Bulgaria in the Eurovision Song Contest 2017|runners-up]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://eurovision.tv/event/kyiv-2017/grand-final/participants |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170515092839/https://eurovision.tv/event/kyiv-2017/grand-final/participants |title=Grand Final Participants |website=eurovision.tv |publisher=[[European Broadcasting Union]] |accessdate=June 12, 2017 |archivedate=May 15, 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nUnder the [[Voting at the Eurovision Song Contest#Voting systems|previous voting system]], \"Amar pelos dois\" would have scored 417 points, surpassing {{Esccnty|Norway|y=2009}}'s \"[[Fairytale (Alexander Rybak song)|Fairytale]]\" which scored 387 points in {{Escyr|2009}}.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.escxtra.com/2017/05/14/eurovision-2017-old-voting/ |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170612015618/https://www.escxtra.com/2017/05/14/eurovision-2017-old-voting/ |title=An Alternate Universe: Eurovision 2017 Under the Old Voting System |website=escXtra |date=May 14, 2017 |archivedate=June 12, 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Also under the previous voting system, \"Amar pelos dois\" would have received a record of twenty combined sets of 12 points (televote + jury vote), overcoming the eighteen maximum scores collected by {{Esccnty|Sweden|y=2012}}'s \"[[Euphoria (Loreen song)|Euphoria]]\" in {{Escyr|2012}}. Thus, from a combined vote perspective, Portugal received 12 points from Armenia, Austria, Belgium, Czech Republic, Estonia, Finland, France, Germany, Iceland, Israel, Lithuania, the Netherlands, Norway, San Marino, Slovenia, Spain, Sweden, Switzerland, Ukraine and the United Kingdom.<ref name=\"Classic voting\">{{cite web|url=https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1-sT2lLmqv-40THcOUbT6pFc7YZm8g9bAhzLx8kkyiCM/edit#gid=31282450|title=Eurovision 2017 Old Voting||publisher=escXtra|accessdate=June 12, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==== Points awarded to Portugal ====\nBelow is a breakdown of points awarded to Portugal in the first semi-final and grand final of the contest, and the breakdown of the televoting and jury voting conducted during the two shows. The country finished in first place on both occasions. In the semi-final, Portugal was ranked first with 370 points overall, garnering 197 from the televote and 173 from the jury vote.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://eurovision.tv/story/exclusive-results-semi-finals-2017 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170522215347/https://eurovision.tv/story/exclusive-results-semi-finals-2017 |title=EXCLUSIVE: Here are the results of the Semi-Finals! |website=eurovision.tv |publisher=[[European Broadcasting Union]] |last=Jordan |first=Paul |date=May 13, 2017 |archivedate=May 22, 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Portugal received 12 points from the televoters in [[Albania in the Eurovision Song Contest 2017|Albania]], [[Belgium in the Eurovision Song Contest 2017|Belgium]], [[Finland in the Eurovision Song Contest 2017|Finland]], [[Iceland in the Eurovision Song Contest 2017|Iceland]], [[Latvia in the Eurovision Song Contest 2017|Latvia]], [[Poland in the Eurovision Song Contest 2017|Poland]], [[Slovenia in the Eurovision Song Contest 2017|Slovenia]], [[Spain in the Eurovision Song Contest 2017|Spain]] and [[Sweden in the Eurovision Song Contest 2017|Sweden]], and received 12 points from the juries of [[Azerbaijan in the Eurovision Song Contest 2017|Azerbaijan]], [[Georgia in the Eurovision Song Contest 2017|Georgia]], Iceland, Latvia, [[Moldova in the Eurovision Song Contest 2017|Moldova]], Poland and Spain.<ref>{{cite web|title=Portugal - First Semi-Final Scoreboard |url=https://eurovision.tv/event/kyiv-2017/first-semi-final/scoreboard/portugal |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170612001437/https://eurovision.tv/event/kyiv-2017/first-semi-final/scoreboard/portugal |website=eurovision.tv |publisher=[[European Broadcasting Union]] |accessdate=June 12, 2017 |archivedate=June 12, 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In the end, Portugal won the contest with 758 points overall; 376 from the televote and 382 from the jury vote. In the grand final, Portugal earned a total of thirty sets of 12 points. The country received maximum scores from the televoters in [[Austria in the Eurovision Song Contest 2017|Austria]], Belgium, Finland, [[France in the Eurovision Song Contest 2017|France]], [[Germany in the Eurovision Song Contest 2017|Germany]], Iceland, [[Israel in the Eurovision Song Contest 2017|Israel]], [[Lithuania in the Eurovision Song Contest 2017|Lithuania]], the [[Netherlands in the Eurovision Song Contest 2017|Netherlands]], [[Norway in the Eurovision Song Contest 2017|Norway]], Spain and [[Switzerland in the Eurovision Song Contest 2017|Switzerland]], and received top marks from the juries of [[Armenia in the Eurovision Song Contest 2017|Armenia]], [[Czech Republic in the Eurovision Song Contest 2017|Czech Republic]], France, Georgia, [[Hungary in the Eurovision Song Contest 2017|Hungary]], Iceland, Israel, Latvia, Lithuania, the Netherlands, Poland, [[San Marino in the Eurovision Song Contest 2017|San Marino]], [[Serbia in the Eurovision Song Contest 2017|Serbia]], Slovenia, Spain, Sweden, Switzerland and the [[United Kingdom in the Eurovision Song Contest 2017|United Kingdom]].<ref name=Scoreboard>{{cite web|title=Portugal - 2017 Grand Final Scoreboard|url=https://eurovision.tv/event/kyiv-2017/grand-final/scoreboard/portugal |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20170612002917/https://eurovision.tv/event/kyiv-2017/grand-final/scoreboard/portugal |website=eurovision.tv |publisher=[[European Broadcasting Union]] |accessdate=June 12, 2017 |archivedate=June 12, 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable collapsible collapsed\"\n|-\n!colspan=\"5\"| Points awarded to Portugal (Semi-final 1)\n|-\n!colspan=\"5\"| Televote\n|-\n!width=20%|12 points\n!width=20%|10 points\n!width=20%|8 points\n!width=20%|7 points\n!width=20%|6 points\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" |\n*{{Esc|Albania|y=2017}}\n*{{Esc|Belgium|y=2017}}\n*{{Esc|Finland|y=2017}}\n*{{Esc|Iceland|y=2017}}\n*{{Esc|Latvia|y=2017}}\n*{{Esc|Poland|y=2017}}\n*{{Esc|Slovenia|y=2017}}\n*{{Esc|Spain|y=2017}}\n*{{Esc|Sweden|y=2017}}\n| valign=\"top\" |\n*{{Esc|Australia|y=2017}}\n*{{Esc|Greece|y=2017}}\n*{{Esc|Italy|y=2017}}\n*{{Esc|United Kingdom|y=2017}}\n| valign=\"top\" |\n*{{Esc|Azerbaijan|y=2017}}\n*{{Esc|Georgia|y=2017}}\n| valign=\"top\" |\n*{{Esc|Armenia|y=2017}}\n*{{Esc|Czech Republic|y=2017}}\n*{{Esc|Montenegro|y=2017}}\n| valign=\"top\" |\n*{{Esc|Cyprus|y=2017}}\n*{{Esc|Moldova|y=2017}}\n|-\n!width=20%|5 points\n!width=20%|4 points\n!width=20%|3 points\n!width=20%|2 points\n!width=20%|1 point\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" |\n| valign=\"top\" |\n| valign=\"top\" |\n| valign=\"top\" |\n| valign=\"top\" |\